as noticed a clear discharge from her nipples.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mastitis","Intraductal papilloma","Fibrocystic change","Cyclical mastalgia","Fibroadenoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of breast pain, lumpiness, and nipple discharge is most characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Efibrocystic change\u003C/strong\u003E. This common condition affects many women of reproductive age and typically fluctuates with the menstrual cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMastitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with breast erythema, warmth, and tenderness, often associated with breastfeeding. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntraductal papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with unilateral, spontaneous, bloody nipple discharge from a single duct. \u003Cstrong\u003ECyclical mastalgia\u003C/strong\u003E presents primarily with breast pain related to the menstrual cycle without significant lumps or discharge. \u003Cstrong\u003EFibroadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a firm, mobile, painless mass without nipple discharge.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fibrocystic change is the most common benign breast condition, affecting up to 50% of women of reproductive age.","The classic triad of fibrocystic change includes breast pain, lumpiness, and nipple discharge.","Fibrocystic changes typically fluctuate with the menstrual cycle due to hormonal influences."],"references":["Bennett DL, Buckley A, Lee MV. Fibrocystic Change. Radiol Clin North Am. 2024 Jul;62(4):581-592. doi: 10.1016/j.rcl.2023.12.008. Epub 2024 Mar 7. PMID: 38777535.","Dang BQ, Miles B, Young P, He J, Nguyen QD. An Interesting Imaging Presentation of a Common Benign Entity: Fibrocystic Changes in a Postmenopausal Patient. Cureus. 2023 Mar 17;15(3):e36292. doi: 10.7759/cureus.36292. PMID: 37073209; PMCID: PMC10106097.","Malherbe K, Khan M, Fatima S. Fibrocystic Breast Disease. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31869073.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53072"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16223"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53072"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T08:35:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T08:35:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8914"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67620"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda